1
00:00:00,352 --> 00:00:29,007
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhasa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhasa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhasa Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-awakened one.

2
00:00:30,625 --> 00:00:35,155
So I thought this evening we'd tackle this factor of enlightenment.

3
00:00:35,756 --> 00:00:42,593
The word is Pasadi and it translates as calmness, tranquility, serenity.

4
00:00:44,107 --> 00:00:51,558
And you can see that this is really important because the Buddha has included it in one of the seven factors of enlightenment.

5
00:00:52,200 --> 00:01:06,302
So, just to remind you, the seven factors are awareness, and you've got effort and concentration, you've got this calmness and curiosity, and then you have...

6
00:01:06,585 --> 00:01:10,310
equanimity and the investigation of the Dharma.

7
00:01:10,549 --> 00:01:15,655
So the first six are just general virtues that everybody can develop.

8
00:01:16,096 --> 00:01:35,075
What turns them into factors of enlightenment is the investigation of the characteristics of existence, impermanence, how we create suffering for ourselves through wrong attachments, wrong desires, wanting, not wanting, and of course, identity, not self.

9
00:01:35,096 --> 00:01:35,495
Okay.

10
00:01:37,112 --> 00:01:44,646
So I think people who've done, if you've done Yoga Nidra, then I think that's a really deep way of relaxing.

11
00:01:46,228 --> 00:01:52,179
And we have to, yeah, in war zones, you have to keep calm and carry on.

12
00:01:52,980 --> 00:01:57,028
So I don't know whether I want to post that up in present war zones.

13
00:01:57,909 --> 00:01:58,911
Terrible what's happening.

14
00:02:00,393 --> 00:02:01,314
So...

15
00:02:02,829 --> 00:02:06,194
The first, the Buddha always splits everything into body and mind.

16
00:02:06,653 --> 00:02:08,695
So if we look at what happens in the body.

17
00:02:09,217 --> 00:02:10,397
So I did a bit of research.

18
00:02:10,478 --> 00:02:13,781
Most of you know this better than I do, actually, for sure.

19
00:02:14,822 --> 00:02:17,806
Remember, we have autonomic systems.

20
00:02:17,925 --> 00:02:21,088
So one is the sympathetic, one is the parasympathetic.

21
00:02:21,590 --> 00:02:24,331
So the sympathetic one is the fight and flight.

22
00:02:25,152 --> 00:02:28,056
So you're walking across the road and a car suddenly makes for you.

23
00:02:28,336 --> 00:02:30,239
Before you know it, you've got to the other side.

24
00:02:30,558 --> 00:02:32,600
So that's the sympathetic.

25
00:02:33,205 --> 00:02:34,306
Nervous system.

26
00:02:34,325 --> 00:02:36,188
The Padawan is the opposite, right?

27
00:02:36,248 --> 00:02:40,574
So it's about calmness, rest and digest.

28
00:02:40,634 --> 00:02:41,735
I've picked that up somewhere.

29
00:02:43,397 --> 00:02:45,600
It affects your heart rate, et cetera, et cetera.

30
00:02:45,621 --> 00:02:46,562
We'll come to that in a minute.

31
00:02:47,082 --> 00:03:01,861
So the big thing about being calm, about relaxing into the present moment is physically it releases all these wonderful neurotransmitters, serotonin, which makes you feel happy and well-being.

32
00:03:02,500 --> 00:03:05,409
and feel-good factors, the endorphins.

33
00:03:06,513 --> 00:03:15,462
Now, remember that in Buddhist understanding, these hormones within the body affect the mind, right?

34
00:03:15,848 --> 00:03:18,411
So there are two different systems within us.

35
00:03:18,550 --> 00:03:30,525
There's this more gross energy that we call subatomic particles, or subatomic energy, and there's a mental energy which is separate from that.

36
00:03:31,045 --> 00:03:33,729
This you can actually experience in your meditation.

37
00:03:34,590 --> 00:03:44,741
So it's not as though these hormones directly make you happy, they just have the effect on the heart of making it happy, your emotional life.

38
00:03:44,924 --> 00:03:46,325
And of course, it works the other way.

39
00:03:46,507 --> 00:03:48,248
When you're angry, the body gets hot.

40
00:03:51,253 --> 00:03:53,397
Similarly, it reduces cortisol.

41
00:03:53,437 --> 00:04:01,431
So that's what we we have when we've got all this stress related stuff, you know, which isn't very good for us.

42
00:04:02,407 --> 00:04:10,878
Because you're relaxed, because the body is feeling okay, obviously it's much better for our immune system.

43
00:04:11,340 --> 00:04:15,526
So we're able to fight diseases.

44
00:04:16,528 --> 00:04:23,137
As you know, there's a syndrome where people who are stressed at work, they go on holiday and then fall ill.

45
00:04:24,059 --> 00:04:28,245
So it's as though they have to have a real rest.

46
00:04:30,723 --> 00:04:32,985
So it lowers muscle tension.

47
00:04:33,005 --> 00:04:34,908
I mean, that's the whole point of relaxing, isn't it?

48
00:04:34,988 --> 00:04:38,774
To relax the muscles as such.

49
00:04:39,475 --> 00:04:42,579
And this, of course, can alleviate even chronic pain.

50
00:04:44,122 --> 00:04:50,031
Just going back to my first episode with my back, the first time the...

51
00:04:50,939 --> 00:05:01,576
the disc prolapsed, I went along to an acupuncturist and I was surprised that as the needles went in, this anxiety came up.

52
00:05:01,596 --> 00:05:11,454
And as the anxiety dissipated, the pain wasn't anywhere near as bad as when I had this anxiety holding the body as it were for me.

53
00:05:11,834 --> 00:05:12,916
It was trying to protect me.

54
00:05:13,177 --> 00:05:16,002
I mean, these systems are trying to protect us.

55
00:05:17,752 --> 00:05:21,257
And similarly, of course, it helps digestion.

56
00:05:23,440 --> 00:05:30,149
It actually talks, it actually says that stress can lead to digestive issues such as indigestion, irritable bowel syndrome.

57
00:05:30,170 --> 00:05:42,608
So especially to feel relaxed around eating, you know, I mean, if you're at work and you're being pressured and you're just chucking the sandwich down your throat, can't be doing you good, can it?

58
00:05:43,488 --> 00:05:47,254
And in Eastern understanding, I was thinking of the Chinese.

59
00:05:47,521 --> 00:05:52,829
11 o'clock to 1 o'clock is eating time.

60
00:05:53,009 --> 00:05:56,394
So your body is primed to eat at that time.

61
00:05:57,235 --> 00:06:01,440
And from 1 o'clock to 3 o'clock is liver time, right?

62
00:06:01,800 --> 00:06:08,992
So if you're rushing around while your liver's trying to handle all these nutrients, you can see it's not going to do you very good.

63
00:06:09,773 --> 00:06:14,478
So between 11 and 3 o'clock, make an effort to be a bit more relaxed.

64
00:06:14,499 --> 00:06:15,620
That's if you're stressed, yeah.

65
00:06:17,845 --> 00:06:22,213
As a change in brain activity, you get these lovely alpha brain waves.

66
00:06:22,673 --> 00:06:26,119
So these are the ones that you have when you're feeling relaxed.

67
00:06:26,158 --> 00:06:28,122
It's also a very creative place to be.

68
00:06:29,024 --> 00:06:30,908
And we're there when we meditate.

69
00:06:31,548 --> 00:06:39,161
So when you're actually in that state of just vipassana, normally the mind will go down to these alpha waves.

70
00:06:41,588 --> 00:06:49,117
And obviously it improves your sleep because, you know, if you're not calm when you go, when you're trying to sleep, it's difficult.

71
00:06:49,137 --> 00:06:49,298
Yeah.

72
00:06:49,317 --> 00:07:01,673
I mean, that's why really, you know, to close everything down about half an hour before we intend to sleep, you know, get off the social media, turn off Netflix, the BBC.

73
00:07:02,547 --> 00:07:04,910
And do something which is going to calm us.

74
00:07:05,271 --> 00:07:14,502
Like, you know, I personally sometimes listen to the chanting from Throstle Hole Abbey, which was my first Buddhist encounter.

75
00:07:15,002 --> 00:07:16,365
And I just love their chanting.

76
00:07:16,665 --> 00:07:19,689
But there's other types of music, read poetry.

77
00:07:19,709 --> 00:07:27,019
There's many things you can do that are just relaxing in order to be prepared to go into sleep, you see.

78
00:07:27,791 --> 00:07:32,737
What we want to do is get that substrate under sleep to be calm and peaceful.

79
00:07:33,418 --> 00:07:41,026
And of course, when we're in bed, to put the breath, to put the attention on the breath and just feel it, just feel the body breathing.

80
00:07:41,326 --> 00:07:43,369
See, it wafts you into sleep, very calm.

81
00:07:44,370 --> 00:07:46,752
I can do metta, of course, yeah?

82
00:07:46,773 --> 00:07:51,538
But the big thing is this sense of being relaxed, of being at ease.

83
00:07:54,269 --> 00:07:55,790
I'm actually reading a book on this.

84
00:07:56,031 --> 00:08:01,238
It was a bestseller, Sunday Times bestseller called Breath by James Nestor.

85
00:08:01,699 --> 00:08:02,800
It's entertaining.

86
00:08:03,583 --> 00:08:04,163
It's very good.

87
00:08:05,425 --> 00:08:15,399
So, OK, when we relax, when we feel calm, even in situations that are stressful, we can, you know, we can get into a calmer place.

88
00:08:16,081 --> 00:08:19,925
It's obviously having these effects on the body and that's got to be good for us.

89
00:08:20,047 --> 00:08:20,326
Yeah.

90
00:08:22,923 --> 00:08:38,351
And when it comes to chittanupasati, the calmness, tranquility of the heart, so obviously the stress is happening the other way.

91
00:08:38,392 --> 00:08:46,246
It's coming as a reaction we have to a given situation or person.

92
00:08:46,936 --> 00:08:50,943
that stress coming in the heart is moving back into the body.

93
00:08:51,424 --> 00:09:00,743
So as soon as we can, you know, just relax around something which is upsetting us, making us anxious, all the better.

94
00:09:03,472 --> 00:09:18,720
And of course, if we have a sort of habit of being calm in situation, it should extend itself into situations which are stressful, which means that we're slightly more emotionally resilient.

95
00:09:18,799 --> 00:09:20,442
We can move our emotions a bit.

96
00:09:20,523 --> 00:09:27,134
We're not stuck on one groove of being angry or being anxious or getting depressed about something.

97
00:09:29,511 --> 00:09:33,839
And of course, when you are calm, it just improves your decision making.

98
00:09:34,801 --> 00:09:40,028
I make a rule for myself, which whenever I break it, it's always disastrous.

99
00:09:40,649 --> 00:09:48,442
I try never to make any decision when I'm miffed or angry, when I'm anxious or when I'm in doubt.

100
00:09:49,024 --> 00:09:54,472
If I make a decision in those states of mind, it's something bad turns up.

101
00:09:55,921 --> 00:09:57,844
So you have to wait sometimes.

102
00:09:57,864 --> 00:10:01,909
You have to wait until there's calmness and then there's greater clarity.

103
00:10:03,993 --> 00:10:06,716
I mean, it's obviously better for our relationships too, isn't it?

104
00:10:06,777 --> 00:10:10,462
I mean, you know, if you're with somebody who's a neurotic, it sort of affects you, doesn't it?

105
00:10:11,403 --> 00:10:13,547
And if you're a neurotic, it affects them.

106
00:10:14,187 --> 00:10:16,191
So if we can sort of

107
00:10:16,340 --> 00:10:40,996
get into the habit of just being calm not rushing you know in conversation you know not trying to uh get the answer ready before the person stopped talking you know but to actually get into that mode of listening and to listen you've got to be calm right you've got to be open right uh it's obviously a good place for creativity uh we're not talking about you know um

108
00:10:41,753 --> 00:10:49,105
you know, winners of the Booker Prize or ecstatic artists.

109
00:10:49,304 --> 00:10:52,330
It's just daily being creative about what we do.

110
00:10:52,990 --> 00:10:58,099
So even washing the pots can be actually a creative action, right?

111
00:10:58,119 --> 00:10:59,981
You can find different ways of doing it.

112
00:11:01,413 --> 00:11:06,437
This creativity, I mean, every moment, every day is different.

113
00:11:06,518 --> 00:11:10,261
So without us knowing it, we've got to be creative, right?

114
00:11:10,282 --> 00:11:13,884
Even if you're driving a car, you've got to be creative.

115
00:11:13,904 --> 00:11:15,287
You've got to see where you're going.

116
00:11:15,326 --> 00:11:21,452
You've got to drive in a safe and easy way and feel relaxed.

117
00:11:21,472 --> 00:11:28,500
So you know what happens when you drive and you're tense and you're anxious to get to a place or you're late to get to a place.

118
00:11:28,480 --> 00:11:33,466
So that's how accidents happen.

119
00:11:35,908 --> 00:11:40,875
So obviously being calm just has an effect on our mental health.

120
00:11:42,017 --> 00:11:52,309
And, you know, developing that as a base within our lives from which we move, right, out of that base you sort of move into an action.

121
00:11:52,330 --> 00:11:54,673
I mean, it's got to make us happy, hasn't it?

122
00:11:55,986 --> 00:11:58,149
Remember, these things are just habits.

123
00:11:58,169 --> 00:11:59,832
They're just habits that we can develop.

124
00:12:01,716 --> 00:12:06,822
So, OK, so it obviously has an effect on the body and it affects on the heart.

125
00:12:07,705 --> 00:12:13,253
And so it now becomes a Bojanga, which is a factor of enlightenment.

126
00:12:14,059 --> 00:12:17,686
And it looms quite large in the Buddha's teachings.

127
00:12:17,765 --> 00:12:21,831
It's normally connected to concentration, calm concentration.

128
00:12:21,932 --> 00:12:27,120
Samatha is the word for calming exercises.

129
00:12:27,179 --> 00:12:31,706
So metta practice would be a samatha practice.

130
00:12:31,726 --> 00:12:35,273
And it leads into an easy concentration.

131
00:12:37,135 --> 00:12:41,923
If you want to be concentrated, the worst thing you can do is to try to be concentrated.

132
00:12:42,089 --> 00:12:53,548
The whole thing about concentration comes when you're relaxed and at ease and just placing the attention on the object and allowing the concentration to manifest.

133
00:12:54,168 --> 00:13:00,840
As soon as you try and push the process, you're getting in the way and what you get is restlessness.

134
00:13:02,254 --> 00:13:03,996
So you find it in the Eightfold Path.

135
00:13:04,057 --> 00:13:07,100
The last three are to do with mindfulness.

136
00:13:07,260 --> 00:13:11,506
It's right effort, right mindfulness, right concentration.

137
00:13:12,027 --> 00:13:15,511
And we can include in that concentration, that sense of calmness.

138
00:13:17,575 --> 00:13:19,777
It's one of the four divine abidings.

139
00:13:19,918 --> 00:13:21,679
So we've got love, compassion.

140
00:13:21,740 --> 00:13:25,745
There come divine abidings, also illimitables.

141
00:13:26,144 --> 00:13:29,730
But there are social virtues, the love, compassion, joy,

142
00:13:29,996 --> 00:13:32,379
And there the word is upeka.

143
00:13:32,720 --> 00:13:39,629
And this is where you get that sort of touching of calmness and equanimity.

144
00:13:40,230 --> 00:13:43,173
So equanimity has to rest upon calmness.

145
00:13:43,734 --> 00:13:47,239
You can't be equanimous if you're all agitated.

146
00:13:48,039 --> 00:13:54,288
Equanimous, in my understanding, refers to a certain attitude, a certain way of looking at things.

147
00:13:54,788 --> 00:13:58,332
Calmness is your mental state and it's supporting it.

148
00:14:01,267 --> 00:14:03,090
Yeah, it's in meditation.

149
00:14:03,149 --> 00:14:15,091
The concentration of the Samatha practice, of course, leads to an even deeper sense of relaxation through the practice of jhana, through the practice of absorptions.

150
00:14:15,111 --> 00:14:17,515
So it's right there within the practice.

151
00:14:17,596 --> 00:14:19,178
It's not something that we add on.

152
00:14:19,679 --> 00:14:22,144
It's a necessary part of our practice.

153
00:14:23,373 --> 00:14:47,129
And when we are calm and we're not restless, whenever something arises, which is obstructing our meditation, messing us about in ordinary daily life, even from minor silly things to sort of heavy mental states, that calmness, if we've got that substrate of calmness, we can deal with it.

154
00:14:47,910 --> 00:14:48,451
That's the point.

155
00:14:52,211 --> 00:14:55,557
And then finally, of course, there is the great calmness itself.

156
00:14:57,159 --> 00:15:06,835
In the Metta Sutta, remember, it talks about what must be done for those people who wish to reach the state of peace.

157
00:15:07,475 --> 00:15:10,039
Now, they use a different word there, Santa.

158
00:15:10,340 --> 00:15:15,248
But of course, it is this calmness, this state of sublime serenity.

159
00:15:15,788 --> 00:15:19,114
That's one of the adjectives the Buddha uses for Nibbana.

160
00:15:21,236 --> 00:15:22,097
So there we are.

161
00:15:22,458 --> 00:15:30,011
So I'm hoping that you're all convinced and, you know, that to develop our calmness is absolutely necessary.

162
00:15:30,812 --> 00:15:38,485
And just remind yourself, it could become part of your New Year resolutions.

163
00:15:38,546 --> 00:15:39,807
A bit late, but why not?

164
00:15:39,888 --> 00:15:42,592
We can always add them on, can't we?

165
00:15:42,873 --> 00:15:45,658
And to sort of...

166
00:15:46,447 --> 00:16:00,350
get in the habit, uh, something I've been working on all my, all my life since I became a Buddhist is to, when you finish something, when you've done a task, it can be just like, you know, the washing of the pots, but it could be a piece of work.

167
00:16:00,450 --> 00:16:03,173
It could be a bit of gardening you've done, not this time, of course.

168
00:16:03,955 --> 00:16:12,488
And when it's finished, just to sort of relax for a moment and just reflect on what you've done and see how you feel about it.

169
00:16:14,532 --> 00:16:14,692
Yeah.

170
00:16:14,792 --> 00:16:14,851
Um,

171
00:16:15,423 --> 00:16:20,732
And then just to stop for a moment, just to relax into the present moment, you see.

172
00:16:20,753 --> 00:16:24,100
And then quite naturally, the next thing to be done will arise, you see.

173
00:16:24,580 --> 00:16:29,409
So you're moving into the next thing to be done from that base of calmness.

174
00:16:31,113 --> 00:16:35,861
And that allows us to be more wise, more loving, you know.

175
00:16:37,259 --> 00:16:51,133
So I'm hoping that I've convinced you to really practice this quality of calmness and that by your devotion to it, you will be liberated from all suffering sooner rather than later.

